Prepare data

Load data from churn.csv then split data into 70% for train and 30% for test.

## Split function
train_test_split <- function(data, size=0.7) {
  set.seed(24)
  n <- nrow(data)
  train_id <- sample(1:n, size*n)
  train_df <- data[train_id, ]
  test_df <- data[-train_id, ]
  return (list(train_df, test_df))
}

## Read data
df <- read_csv("churn.csv")

Train model

Use caret to train logistic regression and knn model. For train glm and knn model will setup trainControl to use: - k-fold cross-validation will be used for resampling. - Sets the number of folds for cross-validation to 10. - Repeats the entire cross-validation process 5 times.

Confusion Matrices:

  • Logistic Regression: Successfully identifies 8 out of 202 âYesâ cases, but misses 194.
  • KNN: Fails to identify any âYesâ cases, misclassifying all 202 as âNo.â
  • This suggests that Logistic Regression has a better ability to detect the minority âYesâ class, albeit with a high number of false negatives.
  • Precision: Logistic Regression has a precision of 0.667, meaning that when it predicts âYes,â itâs correct 66.7% of the time. KNN has undefined precision as it never predicts âYes.â
  • Recall: Logistic Regression has a recall of 0.04, indicating that it only detects 4% of the actual âYesâ cases. KNN has a recall of 0, missing all âYesâ cases.
  • F1-Score: Logistic Regressionâs F1-score of 0.075 balances precision and recall, but itâs still quite low, suggesting a poor balance between identifying âYesâ cases and avoiding false positives. KNNâs F1-score is undefined.
